"Shafir H., Alpert P.","Regional and local climatic effects on the Dead-Sea evaporation",2011,"Climatic Change","105","3-4",,"455","468",,,10.1007/s10584-010-9892-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952755519&partnerID=40&md5=edcca9c7294a9b593eb18a8875459bba","Department of Geophysics and Planetary Sciences, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel","Shafir, H., Department of Geophysics and Planetary Sciences, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel; Alpert, P., Department of Geophysics and Planetary Sciences, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel","The natural evaporation in the Dead-Sea is a very important meteorological parameter to the local industries at Sdom. It was found that the pan evaporation in Sdom has recently increased by 20-25%. In this paper we explore the reasons for this increase. It is found that both large-scale and local climatic changes have contributed to the evaporation increase in the Dead Sea Valley. The large-scale (global) change potentially associated with the global warming, resulted in changes of the frequencies of some synoptic systems in the region. The local change is a result of the recent Dead-Sea drying, which reduced the local Dead-Sea breeze while intensifying the Mediterranean-Sea breeze penetrating the Dead Sea Valley. It is suggested that while the local effect was the dominant climatic change factor in the Dead-Sea Valley in the 1970-1990, the global effect becomes the dominant one in the more recent evaporation increase in the Dead-Sea. © 2010 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Climatic changes; Climatic effects; Dead Sea; Global effects; Local effects; Meteorological parameters; Natural evaporation; Pan evaporation; Sea breeze; Synoptic systems; Evaporation; Global warming; Landforms; Phase transitions; evaporation; frequency analysis; global warming; meteorology; Dead Sea",,,,,,"Alpert, P., Eppel, A., A proposed index for mesoscale activity (1985) J Clim Appl Meteorol, 24, pp. 472-48